-- Specifying Colours With RGB Values ---------------------------------

As well as specifying colours by their names, it is also possible to
specify them with RGB (Red, Green, Blue) values. These indicate how much
red, green, or blue composes each individual colour. These are usually
specified in the following manner:

                              #rrrrggggbbbb

where "r", "g", and "b" are hexadecimal numbers indicating the amount of
each primary colour involved. Numbers with fewer than 12 digits are
padded out with zeros following each primary colour field. For example:

                                  #rgb

is the same as:

                              #r000g000b000

It is usually *not* recommended that this representation for colours be
used since different monitors produce different shades when given the
same inputs. Colour names are more portable since they are usually
adjusted by the supplier to appear roughly similar on different systems.
The problem with colour names is that their is no standard naming
scheme.

Developers of X programs should always ensure that the colours used by
their application are easily tailorable by the user.

Some example RGB specifications are:

            black : #000
            yellow: #ffffffff0000 (red & green, but no blue)



